Part A: Conceptual Questions

A1.

Authors support the claim that it is unethical to include outliers without reporting or removing them for many reasons. One reason is that the addition of the outlier affects the conclusions in such way that the findings no longer represent the majority of the data. As practitioners of science, one should run two models (one with the outliers and one without). If the model changes drastically, one should consider removing the outliers.

A2.

a=.988, b=.367, c=3.65 indirect effect = a*b = .988 x .367 = 0.363 direct effect = c - ab = 3.65 - 0.363 = 3.287

A3.

Based on the information given, you can not conclude that the data are consistent with the hypothesized mediation model. This is because condition four requires the effect of x on y must be smaller when controlling for m. Considering the confidence interval contains 0, therefore the estimate is not significantly different than 0 and condition four is not met.

A4.

The Sobel test is problematic because it assumes that path a and path b are independent of each other, which may not be the case. The advantage of using a non-parametric bootstrapping method is because it does not assume anything about the distributions and can be applied to smaller samples more accurately.

A5.

The term direct effect might be misleading because there are possible other mediators that can explain the residual variance. In multiple mediation, the direct effect would be the effect of X on Y without M1 or M2.

A6.

b.

False

A7.

Comparing a model with 5 predictors to a model with 3 predictors is not the most useful because you do not know which of the two predictors added are explaining more of the variance.

Part B: Data Analysis

B1.

One possible research question you could address with this dataset is does the amount of resources at home and school affect overall math scores. Another question is does the amount of resources affect how students like math? Lastly you could ask if the global region has an affect on resources.

B2.

Since the study does not include manipulation of variables, this study is correlational. It is identifying association between variables (resources, math scores, etc.).

B5.

The focal predictor is liking math, the covariate is gender, and the outcome is math score. The compact model would be: overall_math_score = b0 + b1students_liking_math. The augmented model would be: overall_math_score = b0 + b1students_liking_math + b2percent_girls

B9.

There is a moderate positive correlation between gross national income and math knowing. There is a moderate positive correlation between school resources and math knowing. Lastly, there is a strong positive correlation between home resources and math knowing.

B10.

The focal predictor is gross national income per capita. The covariates are school and home resources. The compact model would be: overall_math_score = b0 + b1gni_per_capita and the augmented model would be: overall_math_score = b0 + b1gni_per_capita + b2school_resources + b3home_resources

timss <- na.omit(timss)

timss$school_resources_c <- timss$school_resources - mean(timss$school_resources)
timss$home_resources_c <- timss$home_resources - mean(timss$home_resources)

Based on the information I have, I think there might be an issue with multicollinearity especially looking at the correlation matrix. If multicollinearity occurs, the standard errors generally increase.

d_graph <- expand.grid(gni_per_capita = seq(min(timss$gni_per_capita, na.rm = TRUE),
                                            max(timss$gni_per_capita, na.rm = TRUE),
                                            length.out = max(timss$gni_per_capita, na.rm = TRUE) - min(timss$gni_per_capita, na.rm = TRUE) + 1),
                       school_resources = mean(timss$school_resources, na.rm = TRUE),
                       home_resources = mean(timss$home_resources, na.rm = TRUE)
)
d_graph <- ggplotPredict(m_graph, d_graph)

ggplot(timss, aes(x = gni_per_capita, y = overall_math_score)) +
  geom_smooth(data = d_graph, stat = "identity", aes(y = Predicted, ymin = CILo, ymax = CIHi), color = "blue", span = 0.1) +
  theme_bw(base_size = 14) +
  labs(x = "Gross National Income per Capita", y = "TIMSS Score on 4th-Grade Math",
       title = "Countries' Overall Math Scores as a Function of GNI per Capita") +
    scale_x_continuous(breaks = seq(0, 80000, by = 10000), limits = c(0, 80000)) +
    scale_y_continuous(breaks = seq(300, 650, by = 50), limits = c(300, 650))

## B15.

region_averages <- timss %>%
  group_by(global_region) %>%
  summarize(avg_math_score = mean(overall_math_score, na.rm = TRUE),
            avg_gni_per_capita = mean(gni_per_capita, na.rm = TRUE))

ggplot(timss, aes(x = gni_per_capita, y = overall_math_score)) +
  geom_point(aes(color = global_region), alpha = 0.7) + 
  geom_point(data = region_averages, aes(x = avg_gni_per_capita, y = avg_math_score)) +
  labs(x = "GNI per Capita", y = "Overall Math Score",
       title = "Math Score vs. GNI per Capita by Global Region") +
  theme_bw(base_size = 14)

This predictor is not statistically significant. The coefficient for math anxiety is -3.86 - for every unit increase in anxiety, our model predicts a 3.86 unit decrease in integer fluency controlling for other factors. This predictor is statistically significant.

C7.

Condition one states that x must have a significant effect on y. In that model, the p-value was .02 which is statistically significant so condition one is met. Condition two states that x must have a significant effect on m. In that model, the p-value was 0.83 which is not statistically significant so condition two is not met. Condition three states that m must have a significant effect on y while controlling for x. In that model, the p-value was .006 which is statistically significant so condition three is met. However, since condition two was not met, the data is not consistent with the hypothesized mediational model.

C9.

medmodel <- ' 

precise_language ~ A * age_months
integer_fluency ~ CPRIME * age_months + B * precise_language

AB:= A*B # Indirect effect
Total := CPRIME + A*B # Total effect
'
set.seed(123)
fit <- sem(medmodel, data = integer, se = "bootstrap", bootstrap = 1000)
parameterEstimates(fit, ci = TRUE, level = 0.95, boot.ci.type = "perc", zstat = F)
##                lhs op              rhs  label    est    se ci.lower ci.upper
## 1 precise_language  ~       age_months      A  0.047 0.019    0.014    0.089
## 2  integer_fluency  ~       age_months CPRIME  0.373 0.079    0.218    0.528
## 3  integer_fluency  ~ precise_language      B  1.177 0.761   -0.177    2.725
## 4 precise_language ~~ precise_language         1.620 0.271    1.074    2.117
## 5  integer_fluency ~~  integer_fluency        30.867 4.349   21.130   38.192
## 6       age_months ~~       age_months        60.770 0.000   60.770   60.770
## 7               AB :=              A*B     AB  0.055 0.044   -0.007    0.167
## 8            Total :=       CPRIME+A*B  Total  0.429 0.084    0.269    0.603

Path AB has a confidence interval that does include 0. Therefore, the estimate is not significantly different than 0 and condition four is not met.

C10.

As predicted, older children had higher integer fluency than younger children, b = 0.43, F(1,59) = 19.89, p < .001, 2 = .25. We also found that older children tended to use more precise mathematical language when explaining their solutions than younger children, b= 0.047, F(1,59) = 4.88, p < .05, 2 = .08. In order to test for mediation, we estimated a multiple regression model in which we regressed integer fluency on age and precise language. The results revealed that both the effect of precise language, b = 1.12, F(2,58) = 12.59, p<.05, 2 = .07, and the effect of age, b= 0.37, F(2,58) = 12.59, p<.001, 2 = .20, were statistically significant. We then used a bootstrapping procedure to compute a confidence interval around the indirect effect (i.e., the path through the mediator). We used Rosseels (2012) lavaan package in R to estimate the confidence interval. Results revealed that the indirect effect via number of subgroups named had a value of 0.055, the 95% confidence interval ranging from -0.007 to 0.167. The fact that zero falls inside the confidence interval indicates that there is not a statistically significant indirect effect, p > .05.

b0 is -50.64 - this is what our model predicts integer fluency score to be for a participant who is 0 months old and has a score of 0 in backwards digit span. b1 is 1.09 - for every unit increase in backwards digit span, our model predicts a 1.09 unit increase on integer fluency while controlling for age. b2 is 0.44 - for every month older a child is, our model predicts a 0.44 unit increase in integer fluency while controlling for backwards digit span. The standard errors decreased very slightly after removing highly influential data points.
